statement.p:
Calculate the area of the rectangle by adding the areas of each piece. Then use the distributive law to find the product of the algebraic expressions.

rectangle
\blert{\text{Area} = 15x+20}

5(3x+4)=5(3x)+5(4) = 15x + 20


rectangle
\blert{\text{Area} = 2x^2+18x}

2x(x+9)=2x(x)+2x(9)=2x^2+18x


rectangle
\blert{\text{Area} = 12b^2+21b}

3b(4b+7)=3b(4b)+3b(7)=12b^2+21b

subsection.p:
Note how each term of the trinomial product arises from the binomial factors:
	(x+6)(x-4)= \amp x^2+2x-24
		 \amp \blert{\text{F}~~~~~~~\text{O+I}~~~~~~~\text{L}}

solution.p:
We multiply each term of the first factor by each term of the second factor, using the "FOIL" template to keep track of the products.
	(3x-5)(4x+2) \amp =3x(4x)+3x(2)-5(4x)-5(2)
		\amp ~~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{F}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{O}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{I}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{L}}
		 \amp = 12x^2+6x-20x-10  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Combine like terms.}}
		\amp = 12x^2-14x-10

statement.p:
Write the area of each rectangle in two different ways:as the sum of four small areas, and then as one large rectangle, using the formula 
	\text{Area} = \text{length} \times \text{width}



sum of four small areas = one large area


	        rectangles


	        \tikzset{%
	        }
	        \begin{tikzpicture} [scale=.5]
			\def\x{3.7 };
			\def\l{5};
			\def\w{2};
			\draw[magenta!80!black,line width=1mm] (0,0) rectangle (\x,\x);
			\draw[magenta!80!black,line width=1mm] (0,0) rectangle (\x,-\w);
			\draw[magenta!80!black,line width=1mm] (\x,0) rectangle +(\l,\x);
			\draw[magenta!80!black,line width=1mm] (\x,0) rectangle +(\l,-\w);
			\node at (-.6,\x/2) {$x$};
			\node at ({\x/2},{\x+.6}) {$x$};
			\node at ({\x+\l/2},{\x+.6}) {$5$};
			\node at (-.6,-\w/2) {$2$};
	        \end{tikzpicture}






